 complex samples as we go.

00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:14.680
 So we're gonna go into the uppercase sample.

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:18.820
 Now the previous thing we did was a loop and this is really more of an if test.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:23.840
 We're not gonna do a loop and the next thing we're going to have an if test and a loop.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:27.680
 So we're going to, we're not gonna store any data here.

00:00:27.680 --> 00:00:28.680
 It's really simple.

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:29.680
 We're just doing an if statement.

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:32.240
 We're gonna check in this one hard-coded valuables.

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:37.120
 We're gonna check to see if p is greater than or less than a.

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:40.800
 So we're gonna load into a the constant p.

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:44.460
 We're gonna compare the constant a with the accumulator.

00:00:44.460 --> 00:00:47.200
 We're doing a convert to uppercase here.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:52.640
 If it's already uppercase, we're going to skip down and if it's not uppercase, we're

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.000
 gonna convert it to uppercase.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.440
 And this will only work for lowercase a through z, but you get the idea, okay?

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:01.560
 So let's take a look here, convert to uppercase.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:05.320
 So let's go ahead and so if we look at these things, we got a load.

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:06.600
 We got our immediate.

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:07.600
 So that's the letter p.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:13.300
 We got our compare and then we have our immediate, which is the letter a and then we have the

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:21.700
 branch of minus down two and the branch of minus is really skipping this subtraction

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:23.080
 and going all the way to eight.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:28.720
 So the if then else that we've kind of got here is if it's minus, we're going to skip

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:32.320
 down two instructions to eight.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:38.440
 If it is not minus, we're going to run six and then that's gonna be a subtract immediate

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:40.520
 of zero x 20.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:46.080
 Hopefully you kind of see that that's a two and that's a zero because the zero x 20, you

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:47.080
 can see those.

00:01:47.080 --> 00:01:49.800
 At some point, you should start seeing the hex.

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:55.240
 Okay, let's go ahead and just run this at full speed and maybe I'll talk a little bit

00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:56.440
 about it afterwards.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:01:58.840
 I'm just going to turn on narration and fire.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.440
 Oh no, I'm going to step, I'm going to step.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:03.420
 So let's do the first one.

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:06.400
 Let's load the letter p into the accumulator.

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:13.120
 PC zero x zero zero load accumulator immediate zero x seven zero.

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:16.200
 So that's a zero x seven zero, which is lowercase p and ASCII.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:17.200
 Oh, hang on.

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:19.420
 Let me bring up the ASCII chart, right?

00:02:19.420 --> 00:02:22.400
 So now we can bring up the ASCII chart, so that's kind of fun.

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:25.360
 So I got this little ASCII chart for you quick computation.

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:30.280
 So zero x seven zero is a, hopefully, a lowercase p.

00:02:30.280 --> 00:02:31.280
 Look at that.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:33.360
 So zero x seven zero is a lowercase p.

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:39.760
 The assembler converted this from a quote p quote, which is one of its many load accumulator

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:45.520
 syntaxes and it changed it into zero one one one zero zero zero and which is the letter

00:02:45.520 --> 00:02:46.520
 p.

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:49.080
 Now, we're going to compare this with the letter a.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:50.240
 So where is that?

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:53.800
 This is the, we're in instruction two now and we're going to compare it with the a and

00:02:53.800 --> 00:03:04.400
 a is just sixty one hex and there it is, sixty one hex and so let's just compare it, run

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:05.400
 one instruction.

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:11.600
 PC zero x zero two, compare accumulator with immediate zero x six one.

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:21.480
 Okay, so now we basically have it set so that p, which was in the accumulator, is greater

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:22.480
 than a.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:27.680
 We didn't set the zero flag and we didn't set the negative flag, okay?

00:03:27.680 --> 00:03:35.040
 And if this character that we just compared is less than a, then we're going to skip.

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:37.680
 If it's not, we're going to subtract twenty from it.

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:43.360
 So it's not going to be very exciting, this is going to become zero x fifty, because we're

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:45.400
 going to subtract zero x twenty.

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:47.640
 So let's go ahead and run that step.

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:53.960
 PC zero x zero four, branch if minus address zero x zero eight.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:58.680
 The branch didn't get taken, it fell right through into position zero x zero six and

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:00.680
 now we're going to do a subtract.

00:04:00.680 --> 00:04:07.360
 PC zero x zero six, subtract with carry immediate zero x two zero.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:12.320
 So now the next instruction is to stop, but you'll notice that we did subtract that seventy.

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:16.240
 The accumulator was seventy, which is the letter, where were we?

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:22.880
 The letter p, and we subtracted twenty hex to it, which just happens to be uppercase

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:23.880
 p.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:27.000
 So this was a convert to uppercase operation.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.120
 And the last step is just to stop.

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:34.140
 PC zero x zero eight, break, no printed output.

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:35.820
 So we didn't store anything.

00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:41.800
 We just are showing a simple if then else, which turns into a sort of compare and skip

